#Text=William Barksted
#Text=William Barksted
#Text=( fl. 1611 ) was an English actor and poet .
#Text=Biography
#Text=William Barksted in 1609 performed in Ben Jonson ' s Epicene , and in 1613 in Beaumont and Fletcher 's Coxcomb .
#Text=When he performed in Epicene he was of the company " provided and kept " by Kirkham , Hawkins , Kendall , and Payne , and in Jonson 's folio of 1616 he is associated with " Nat .

column1: #Text=Certain documents ( a bond and articles of agreement in connection with Philip Henslowe and Edward Alleyn ) introduce Barksted 's name in 1611 and 1615 – 16 , as belonging to this company of actors referred .
#Text=Nothing later concerning him has been discovered , except an anecdote worked into the Wit and Mirth of John Taylor , the Water Poet , in 1629 .
#Text=In some copies also of the Insatiate Countess , dated 1631 , the name of John Marston is displaced by that of William Barksted .
#Text=It was possibly as actor that he became acquainted with Henry , earl of Oxford , and Elizabeth , countess of Derby .
#Text=The former he calls , in the verse-dedication of Hiren , " the Heroicke Heroes " .
#Text=The Countess of Derby is addressed as " Your honor 's from youth oblig 'd " . ’
#Text=Works
#Text=Barksted was the author of the poems Mirrha , the Mother of Adonis ; or Lustes Prodegies ( 1607 ) ; and Hiren , or the Faire Greeke ( 1611 ) .
#Text=On the title-page of the latter , he describes himself as " one of the servants of his Maiesties Revels " .
#Text=There is a " Prologue to a playe to the cuntry people " in Ashmole MS . 38 ( art . 198 ) , which William Carew Hazlitt attributed to Barksted , that is signed " William Buckstead , Comedian " .

column1: #Text=That which seems
#Text=Best is Worst , exprest in a paraphrastical transcript of Iuvenal 's tenth Satyre .
#Text=Together with the Tragicall Narration of Virginius 's Death interserted
#Text=, London , 1617 .
#Text=This is a paraphrase resembling in method Barksted 's Mirrha , which is paraphrased from the tenth book of Ovid ' s Metamorphoses .
#Text=Both Mirrha and Hiren owe much to " Venus and Adonis " , and their author pays the following tribute to Shakespeare at the close of Mirrha : —

#Text=But stay my Muse in thine owne confines keepe , And wage not warre with so deere lou 'd a neighbor , But hauing sung thy day song , rest and sleepe , Preserue thy small fame and his greater fauor : His song was worthie merrit ( Shakspeare hee ) Sung the faire blossome , thou the withered tree : Lawrell is due to him , his art and wit Hath purchas 'd it , Cypres thy brow will fit .
